    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Louisville Ky&#44;</placeName> <date>April 3d 1854</date></p>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p><persName role="author">B H. Gotthelf</persName></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Walnut St. No 371</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName><hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi></placeName></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Louisville&#44; Kentucky&#44;</placeName> <date>April 3&#44; 1854</date></p>
			<p>Very honored <addressee>Mr. Leeser</addressee>&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Your worthy letter&#44; as well as the books therein noted&#44; have<lb/> arrived. For the books&#44; I have paid &#36;9.75 in express charges which seem<lb/> to me unusually high. You must have patience till the middle day<lb/> of <date>Passover</date>&#44; when I shall take care to distribute the to your honor<lb/> subscribers. I shall also make an effort to sell <hi rend="underline">Dias</hi>. With<lb/> regard to the &#8220;Occident&#8221; namely&#44; its lack of success in this town<lb/> no one is more sorry about it than I. During one year&#44; so<lb/> many have given me notice about it that I could not even<lb/> note down their names. I have taken all sorts of trouble public<lb/> and privately to change this attitude&#59; but in vain. When the time<lb/> for payment comes these people don&#39;t want to have it any more<lb/> The reason for this rests in the lack of a true inner culture<lb/> an old cancer&#44; which it is not within my power to heal. The<lb/> &#8220;Asmonean&#8221; has also no more than five or six readers&#44; and when<lb/> several months ago&#44; someone came here to collect for it several of<lb/> these few gave it up. The gentlemen have no conception of what<lb/> means to support a work of this sort from the very beginning. In<lb/> spite of this&#44; I shall take the trouble to do what I can at the com&#45;<lb/>munal meeting which is to take place in our town during the<lb/> middle days of the holiday. Our friend <persName>Strauss</persName> assured me<lb/> of his cooperation. <persName>L. Lowensohn</persName>&#44; our secretary&#44; complains th<add>&#63;</add><lb/> he has not received an &#8220;Occident&#8221; in months&#44; in spite of the fact<lb/> that he has made inquiries about it every month at the post<lb/> office. It may be that there is another <persName>Lowensohn</persName>&#44; perhaps<lb/> <placeName>Dayton</placeName>&#44; whose copies are returned to you. I beg of you to send<lb/> his copy to our secretary who&#44; though a poor man&#44; is a good <add>&#63;</add><lb/> those he has missed until now I have given him.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I could not hear anything more since then about <persName>Simon</persName><lb/> and <persName>Oppenheimer</persName>&#44; and you will do better therefore to retain the<lb/> copies.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Please send me&#44; with your next letter&#44; as soon as possible<lb/> a list of your subscribers here and in the vicinity so that I may<lb/> be in a position to make collections now and then. I should also<lb/> like to know my own standing with you. Also send me&#44; as<lb/> cheaply as possible&#44; two sets of your pentateuchs&#44; with gilt<lb/> binding&#44; a half dozen prayer&#45;books in ordinary binding&#44; and a half<lb/> dozen in gilt binding&#44; the Ashkanzic ritual. Several of these<lb/> have been ordered from me for <date>Passover</date>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Dr. Wise&#39;s</persName> history arouses little interest here. It<lb/> has about 50 subscribers and only 10 or even fewer have<lb/> taken up the work. <persName>Dr. Kalisch</persName>&#44; too&#44; will fare no better&#44; it<lb/> seems to me. I shall write to you in greater detail after<lb/> <date>Passover</date>&#8212;also a variety of things about the congregation</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">My wife sends you her greetings. Please send me<lb/> at once&#44; through Adam&#39;s Express&#44; the books I ordered&#44; so<lb/> that I might receive them before <date>Passover</date>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(6)">Wishing you a happy holiday&#44; I sign</p>
          <p rend="indent(7)">most respectfully&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(8)">Your devoted servant</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">B. H. Gotthilf</persName></p>
          
        </body>
    </text>
